-- Norilsk, Sberbank, VTB, Gazprom, Lukoil May Move: Russian Equity Preview
-- Paul Abelsky
-- 2010-06-28T04:00:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-28/norilsk-sberbank-vtb-gazprom-lukoil-may-move-russian-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
unusual price changes in Russian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and share prices are from the previous close.  
 Russia’s ruble-based  Micex Index  retreated 1.1 percent to
1,347.58 in Moscow. The 30-stock gauge has fallen 12 percent
from its April 15 peak. The dollar-denominated  RTS Index  slid
1.1 percent to 1,387.66.  
 OAO Norilsk Nickel  (GMKN RX): Russia’s largest mining
company holds an  annual shareholders meeting  today. The company
may pay its first dividend in two years this year,  Oleg Deripaska , the billionaire owner of United Co. Rusal, which
controls a third of Norilsk’s board, said in April. Norilsk
retreated 1.7 percent to 4,804.48 rubles.  
 OAO Sberbank  (SBER03 RX) and  VTB Group  (VTBR RX): Russian
lenders may benefit if European countries press ahead with
“excessively tough” banking industry regulations, said  Arkady Dvorkovich , an economic adviser to President  Dmitry Medvedev .
Sberbank dropped 2.9 percent, the most in one month, to 77.98
rubles. VTB, the country’s second-largest bank, lost 2.1 percent
to 7.7 kopeks.  
 OAO Gazprom  (GAZP RX): Russia’s natural-gas export monopoly
plans to send Deputy Chief Executive Officer  Valery Golubev  to
Minsk this week to settle debts over gas shipments transiting
Belarus, Interfax reported. Russia owes Belarus $32 million for
gas transit shipments, Interfax said, citing Belarusian First
Deputy Prime Minister  Vladimir Semashko . Gazprom fell 1.7
percent to 152.21 rubles.  
 OAO Rosneft : (ROSN RX) and  OAO Lukoil  (LKOH RX): Crude oil
rose the most in two weeks, increasing $2.35 to settle at $78.86
a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange, the biggest gain
since June 9. Rosneft, Russia’s largest oil producer, declined
1.1 percent to 196.48 rubles. Lukoil, Russia’s biggest non-state
oil company, gained 1.1 percent to 1,705.26 rubles.  
